<DOC><DOCNO> AP890310-0264 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0213EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-10 0723</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0757</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastern Airlines filed for protection fromcreditors in bankruptcy court, the sixth day of a Machinists strike,blaming pilots for a ``cash crisis'' that paralyzed the nation'sseventh-largest airline.   The move Thursday came a day after Eastern insisted such a stepremained a last resort in the airline's effort to endure the strike,which had strong support from pilots and flight attendants.   The filing under Chapter 11 in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New Yorkis designed to give Eastern a reprieve from debts while it tries torestructure and extricate itself from the worst crisis in its60-year history.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Bush administration, spurred by the bloodyriots in Venezuela, is putting together a new approach to the heavydebt burden being carried by Third World countries, a problem thatTreasury Secretary Nicholas Brady has called ``perhaps the mostdifficult'' facing the new administration.   The new plan, or at least some details of what it will contain,could be revealed as early as Friday, when Brady is scheduled toaddress a private conference on Third World debt at the StateDepartment.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   William Clay Ford is retiring as a vice chairmanof Ford Motor Co., paving the way for a fourth generation of familyleadership of the automaker founded by his grandfather, Henry Ford.   The retirement of Ford, disclosed Thursday, is effective at theend of March and has been anticipated for months. He will remain onthe board of directors and as chairman of the board's finance andexecutive committees.</TEXT><DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Emhart Corp.'s board of directors rejectedan investment group's unsolicited $2.4 billion takeover offer andsaid it had received rival buyout bids from other parties.   Peter L. Scott, Emhart's chairman, recommended shareholders nottender any of their stock to Topper Acquisition Corp., whoseinvestors include oil heir Gordon P. Getty and New York developersLawrence and Zachary Fisher.   Topper, which has offered $35 a share for Emhart, had noimmediate comment.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A House panel approved legislation to add $1.30an hour to the $3.35 minimum wage over the next three years asDemocratic leaders said they are willing to compromise with the Bushadministration by adding a reduced ``training wage'' for new workers.   The move to raise the minimum for the first time in eight yearswas approved Thursday on a party-line vote by the House laborstandards subcommittee. The bill is nearly identical to one approvedby the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee on Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Taiwanese exporter said it had canceled alarge order for Washington apples because of concerns over thehealth effects of the chemical Alar, the latest sign of slowingsales due to the controversy.   W.L.H. Group of Seattle this week canceled an order for 5,000boxes of Washington apples and may not order any more U.S. applesthe rest of the season, Sue Lin, an employee in the Seattle office,said Thursday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Bush administration said it opposes thecontinuation of preferential tax breaks that federal regulators havebeen using to attract buyers for insolvent savings and loanassociations.   ``Unequivocally, we do not favor the continuation of favorabletax treatment,'' White House Budget Director Richard Darman told theSenate Finance Committee.   Meanwhile, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. on Thursday tookcontrol of an additional 45 failed savings and loans, with $13.6billion in assets, in eight states.</TEXT><DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Mexican government has decided to sell itscontrolling interest in the nation's problem-ridden telephonecompany despite strong union opposition, government and unionsources said.   Such a sale would be the most dramatic example to date ofPresident Carlos Salinas de Gortari's efforts to privatizegovernment-owned companies and modernize the Mexican economy.   ``The problem is to do it without making it sound like anotherconfrontation with a labor union,'' a government source saidThursday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market slipped Thursday as the Dow Jones average of 30industrials dropped 4.11 points to 2,291.43.   The dollar drifted lower against other major currencies.   Bond prices edged lower in quiet trading.   Silver and gold futures prices advanced and grains and soybeansrebounded, while livestock, meat and energy futures retreated.</TEXT></DOC>